Respecting space is huge...

Having a dog who never gives you space, or doesn't respect your space is NOT a flex!

It's a sign that you're relationship with your dog is not functional.

Not functional?

Yup.

If you can't get your dog to give you space, I guarantee you aren't getting your dog to come when called when they don't want to...

Or to hold a down stay....when they don't want to...

You know....the things that keep your dog ALIVE!!

You're relationship is the key to everything.

Step 1 is to accept the reality that it needs some work.

This isn't an accident...

It didn't happen overnight...

A lot of patience was exhibited...

A lot of control was established first, individually...

Many people just see two dogs chilling.

I see a dog with a nasty attitude problem and two attempted unalivings on dogs calmly sharing a valuable space with another dog.

It helps that Elmo is simply AMAZING at diffusing conflict in other dogs.

I had nothing to do with that.

It's who he is.

But even with that, I had a LOT of work to do to make sure if she popped off I could do something about it without question.

When bringing another dog into your home you can cross your fingers and just cut them loose...

Or...

You can show some sense and take your time doing it in a way that intelligently increases the odds of success.

Continuing education is a good thing.

We should never stop learning.

However...

More and more young trainers are investing far more into traveling from seminar to seminar and less time working the dang dogs.

It's good to go learn some fundamentals, especially when it revolves around the principles.

But you have to then spend TIME applying that learning.

Seminar hopping takes more than just money that could be used in better ways, but it takes up something more precious...

TIME

Not to mention that many of the seminars pet dog trainers are going to are teaching things that are fairly specialized to very different contexts...like WORKING dogs and the associated mindsets and behaviors.

Im not saying seminars are bad. If you respond to this post in that context be prepared to be told to work on your reading comprehension and emotional control.

There are some GREAT trainers who specialize in helping pet dog trainers through some of the more challenging cases and behaviors.

Even then, you have to get home and PUT IN THE WORK.

It's too late for this year but if you love your dog this is what you can do to help them for the rest of their life....hire a professional who has proven they can help dogs and their owners with this, and DO WHAT THEY SAY.  DRUGS do NOT solve the real PROBLEM.  They are only a temporary quick fix that should be seen as exactly that.

The hardest part of most challenges is SHOWING UP.

I haven't been on the mats since that one time in 2021.
 
And there were those 3 times back in 2020.

I haven't consistently "trained" since 2017.

Jiu jitsu has been on my mind again though l, a little more than usual.

Yesterday I said to myself "I should go to Ybor for open mat tomorrow.

I wasn't home and didn't have a Gi, so I Amazon'd one. 

Then when I woke up this morning the doubt started creeping in. I started telling myself I'm not in good enough shape, or I might get injured from letting myself go.

BUT...

I'm working on keeping more promises to MYSELF and I said I was going to go.  So I didn't waste anymore time talking that crap to myself.  I got in the car and left, an hour early.

Why?

Action. 

I had to MOVE.

I had to SHOW UP.

As far as what happened when I got there, I had a BLAST.

Of all the things I've ever done, nothing makes me feel the way BJJ does.

And to think, I almost talked myself out of it.

Showing up is often the hardest part, which is why so many of us don't do it enough. 

So do it more.

Make a promise to yourself, and keep it.

Start with one and see what happens.

Just show up.

But hey, I was young, inexperienced, and there were dogs there I could begin my journey on.

Age has taught me to silently watch, and remember, and only say something when asked, which isn't often luckily lol

But I was there too. 

Wearing suits that didn't fit  me or the situation I was wearing them in, because that's all that was available.  Some of them barely offered protection in places.  Even getting creative and making hidden sleeves from road cones (a painful lesson in avoiding too much improvisation)

But I wanted to work

Being put in front of the ball biters because I was the new guy or being given the weak dogs that probably shouldn't even have been being worked (I actually learned the most from those dogs so thank you fellas).

But I wanted to earn my way to learn.

Reinforcing unwanted behaviors, slipping suits when they should have stayed on, and not knowing the precise moment to fold and give the dog the victory.

But I was willing to be wrong to learn to be right, or at least better than the day before.

Maybe it was the lack of a platform for my immature ego to make a scene, or maybe it was my own personality combined with mentors who would never have let false bravado grow let alone take seed...

But I knew my place.

So carry on bitey people.  But try your best to do so in good time, in good measure, and with as much awareness of how far you REALLY have to go.

But that's where being a student counts.
